1
00:00:01,090 --> 00:00:05,630
The VWAP is one of the best trading indicators
for determining intraday momentum.

2
00:00:05,630 --> 00:00:10,750
VWAP, meaning the Volume-Weighted-Average-Price,
tells you a very important piece of information:

3
00:00:10,750 --> 00:00:15,030
the average price at which an instrument is
traded over a given period of time.

4
00:00:15,030 --> 00:00:20,360
Basically, is the total amount of money transacted
during some period divided by the total amount

5
00:00:20,360 --> 00:00:23,350
of volume that traded over the same time frame.

6
00:00:23,350 --> 00:00:28,140
While VWAP is no holy grail, it is an effective
instrument for differentiating between random

7
00:00:28,140 --> 00:00:32,140
(meaning choppy price action) and non-random
(meaning trending behaviour).

8
00:00:32,140 --> 00:00:37,230
That why, in today’s video I will share
how I use the VWAP to time my entries and

9
00:00:37,230 --> 00:00:41,430
I’ll show you the precise pattern I search
for when I’m day trading stocks.

10
00:00:41,430 --> 00:00:47,060
VWAP represents the market's True Average
Price over the plotted length of time, most

11
00:00:47,060 --> 00:00:48,440
commonly a trading day.

12
00:00:48,440 --> 00:00:53,399
While the other popular technical indicators
are displaying data based on a recent number

13
00:00:53,399 --> 00:00:56,300
of candles, the VWAP has a cumulative nature.

14
00:00:56,300 --> 00:01:00,540
That’s the problem with periodic indicators,
like moving averages for example.

15
00:01:00,540 --> 00:01:06,159
Let’s say you selected a 10ema or a 20sma
to trade with.

16
00:01:06,159 --> 00:01:11,560
Data from beyond the look-back period you’ve
selected is no longer factored into the calculation,

17
00:01:11,560 --> 00:01:14,270
leaving you with an incomplete picture of
the market.

18
00:01:14,270 --> 00:01:18,979
VWAP’s cumulative nature allows you to see
the full picture develop over the course of

19
00:01:18,979 --> 00:01:21,719
the day while factoring in each candle.

20
00:01:21,719 --> 00:01:26,340
No piece of data gets left behind, as each
transaction that has occurred should factor

21
00:01:26,340 --> 00:01:31,369
into how you interpret the current state of
the market and what's most likely to happen

22
00:01:31,369 --> 00:01:32,549
next.

23
00:01:32,549 --> 00:01:36,819
Unlike traditional moving averages which simply
sum up the closing price of an instrument

24
00:01:36,819 --> 00:01:42,429
traded and divide it by a number of predetermined
periods, the VWAP gives you the true average

25
00:01:42,429 --> 00:01:49,719
price of the instrument by additionally considering
the transaction volume at a specific price.

26
00:01:49,719 --> 00:01:54,570
In addition to providing increased context,
the cumulative calculation of VWAP prevents

27
00:01:54,570 --> 00:01:59,989
confusion regarding selected chart time frames
and indicator settings that exist in nearly

28
00:01:59,989 --> 00:02:01,890
every other piece of technical analysis.

29
00:02:01,890 --> 00:02:07,319
It doesn’t matter if you use a 1-minute
chart, a 30-min chart, or anything in between.

30
00:02:07,319 --> 00:02:09,230
There is only one intraday VWAP.

31
00:02:09,230 --> 00:02:14,090
Flipping between time frames will affect only
the display of the VWAP behavior, but the

32
00:02:14,090 --> 00:02:16,230
calculation remains constant.

33
00:02:16,230 --> 00:02:21,849
The same can’t be said for periodic indicators,
where a 20-period moving average on a 1-minute

34
00:02:21,849 --> 00:02:26,421
chart will often look drastically different
than it would with any other period, like

35
00:02:26,421 --> 00:02:29,069
the 5-minute chart.

36
00:02:29,069 --> 00:02:34,209
The reason why VWAP is highly effective is
because it acts like a magnet, either attracting

37
00:02:34,209 --> 00:02:35,620
or repelling the price.

38
00:02:35,620 --> 00:02:40,709
For this reason, VWAP indicator can help you
to identify support and resistance levels.

39
00:02:40,709 --> 00:02:45,629
Since the indicator averages the total periods
for the day, it has psychological meaning

40
00:02:45,629 --> 00:02:46,629
on the chart.

41
00:02:46,629 --> 00:02:51,719
If the price approaches the VWAP from below
and starts hesitating in the area, then the

42
00:02:51,719 --> 00:02:53,550
VWAP may be considered resistance.

43
00:02:53,550 --> 00:02:58,579
If this happens in the opposite direction,
then the indicator might be able to support

44
00:02:58,579 --> 00:03:01,400
the price, creating a bullish movement.

45
00:03:01,400 --> 00:03:08,280
Now that we covered the basics of VWAP, let’s
see how we can apply it to day trading and

46
00:03:08,280 --> 00:03:09,280
scalping.

47
00:03:09,280 --> 00:03:13,940
Considering that the VWAP offers dynamic support
or resistance through the day, the trading

48
00:03:13,940 --> 00:03:18,019
plan would be:
• to identify a probable trend that's expected

49
00:03:18,019 --> 00:03:21,580
to continue
• and to enter the trade around VWAP area

50
00:03:21,580 --> 00:03:23,640
with defined risk

51
00:03:23,640 --> 00:03:28,230
If you analyze any chart, you will notice
that when stocks go on strong trends and get

52
00:03:28,230 --> 00:03:33,849
extended from the VWAP, they will at some
point pullback before the continuing trend.

53
00:03:33,849 --> 00:03:36,639
Waiting for this pullback takes patience.

54
00:03:36,639 --> 00:03:41,459
Most novice traders chase the stock when it
is going up, and then sell for a loss because

55
00:03:41,459 --> 00:03:43,629
they bought when it was extended.

56
00:03:43,629 --> 00:03:48,390
The stock almost always pulls back to its
VWAP at some point during the trading day.

57
00:03:48,390 --> 00:03:53,019
That’s why it’s better to wait for the
pullback and don’t chase the market.

58
00:03:53,019 --> 00:03:57,909
This gives you better Reward vs Risk on your
trades and helps you time your entries and

59
00:03:57,909 --> 00:03:58,909
exits.

60
00:03:58,909 --> 00:04:05,040
So the idea is to buy a retracement to VWAP
after a strong upward move and to sell the

61
00:04:05,040 --> 00:04:08,319
retracement after a strong downward move.

62
00:04:08,319 --> 00:04:13,639
But this strategy alone isn’t enough to
record consistent results.

63
00:04:13,639 --> 00:04:17,000
Often times, the price will cut though the
VWAP with ease.

64
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:21,560
It’s not about taking a signal, it’s about
filtering and trading only the high quality

65
00:04:21,560 --> 00:04:22,600
setups.

66
00:04:22,600 --> 00:04:27,190
The greatest value of a trading setup is not
the entry it offers, but the stop-loss it

67
00:04:27,190 --> 00:04:28,260
implies.

68
00:04:28,260 --> 00:04:32,150
For VWAP setups, our stop-loss is always on
the other side of it.

69
00:04:32,150 --> 00:04:37,600
A high quality setup offers a reliable stop-loss
point that the market is unlikely to hit in

70
00:04:37,600 --> 00:04:38,930
the near future.

71
00:04:38,930 --> 00:04:43,950
The stop-loss of a high quality VWAP setup
is often a solid support point in a bullish

72
00:04:43,950 --> 00:04:48,430
market or a resistance point in a bearish
market.

73
00:04:48,430 --> 00:04:53,830
Remember this: a high quality VWAP setup usually
occurs at a key support or resistance level.

74
00:04:53,830 --> 00:05:00,020
A long trading setup at a support area is
superior to one that is located in “no man’s

75
00:05:00,020 --> 00:05:01,020
land”.

76
00:05:01,020 --> 00:05:05,550
A short trading setup is more promising if
it appears as the market tests a resistance

77
00:05:05,550 --> 00:05:07,729
area.

78
00:05:07,729 --> 00:05:12,400
So there are 2 factors you should consider
in assessing the quality of a VWAP trading

79
00:05:12,400 --> 00:05:13,400
setup.

80
00:05:13,400 --> 00:05:19,340
First is the VWAP line on your chart and second,
as we target a pullback of a stock, the 50%

81
00:05:19,340 --> 00:05:21,110
Fibonacci retracement.

82
00:05:21,110 --> 00:05:25,430
What I’ve found out when I was analyzing
trends is that most major moves, and many

83
00:05:25,430 --> 00:05:30,389
minor ones, will eventually retrace to around
the 50% level of the move.

84
00:05:30,389 --> 00:05:35,259
That’s why I started to pay extra attention
to these areas.

85
00:05:35,259 --> 00:05:40,870
To draw effective support/resistance levels
using the concept of 50% retracement, the

86
00:05:40,870 --> 00:05:43,139
key is the price move you choose.

87
00:05:43,139 --> 00:05:47,770
The price move must be a strong one that has
momentum on its side.

88
00:05:47,770 --> 00:05:53,590
I primarily only use the 50% level, but for
me it is an ‘approximate’ 50% retrace,

89
00:05:53,590 --> 00:06:00,060
and that means if a valid signal forms near
the 50% level, say anywhere from a 50% retrace

90
00:06:00,060 --> 00:06:05,430
to a 60% retrace, I will also count that as
a valid retrace.

91
00:06:05,430 --> 00:06:12,750
Now, the strategy is all about finding confluence
between VWAP and the 50% FIB level.

92
00:06:12,750 --> 00:06:16,169
For a long signal:
We look for a bullish price move that clears

93
00:06:16,169 --> 00:06:19,990
above a previous swing high with strong momentum.

94
00:06:19,990 --> 00:06:26,199
We mark out a “retracement zone” between
50% and 61.8% of the price move.

95
00:06:26,199 --> 00:06:31,820
If price falls down to the retracement zone
and the VWAP offers additional support, we

96
00:06:31,820 --> 00:06:36,319
aim to buy a possible rejection of that area.

97
00:06:36,319 --> 00:06:39,460
In this example, we have a first strong upswing.

98
00:06:39,460 --> 00:06:44,229
We have consecutive bullish bars which rose
above the last swing high

99
00:06:44,229 --> 00:06:49,910
We drew the 50% and 61.8% retracement levels
of the bullish move.

100
00:06:49,910 --> 00:06:53,220
The area between them is the retracement zone.

101
00:06:53,220 --> 00:06:58,229
This sharp retracement down found support
at the VWAP, right in the retracement zone.

102
00:06:58,229 --> 00:07:02,250
The candlesticks that followed had lower shadows
implying bullish pressure.

103
00:07:02,250 --> 00:07:07,910
Thus, the confluence area between VWAP and
50% zone was a valid signal and offered a

104
00:07:07,910 --> 00:07:09,419
high probability trade.

105
00:07:09,419 --> 00:07:17,319
Stop loss below the confluence area and ideally,
aim for at least 1:1.5 risk reward ratio.

106
00:07:17,319 --> 00:07:21,849
Please bear in mind that you should evaluate
the market bias before assessing individual

107
00:07:21,849 --> 00:07:23,110
trading setups.

108
00:07:23,110 --> 00:07:26,889
The market bias trumps any individual VWAP
trading setup.

109
00:07:26,889 --> 00:07:31,470
If you get the market bias wrong, regardless
of the quality of the trading setup, it will

110
00:07:31,470 --> 00:07:34,909
not work out over the long run.

111
00:07:34,909 --> 00:07:38,479
For a short signal:
Look for a bearish price move that clears

112
00:07:38,479 --> 00:07:41,490
below the previous swing low with strong momentum.

113
00:07:41,490 --> 00:07:48,110
Mark out a “retracement zone” between
50% and 61.8% of the price move.

114
00:07:48,110 --> 00:07:54,479
If price rises up to the retracement zone
and the VWAP offers additional resistance,

115
00:07:54,479 --> 00:07:58,729
we aim to sell a possible rejection of that
area.

116
00:07:58,729 --> 00:08:02,949
Here we have a bearish move that brought the
market to a new low for the day.

117
00:08:02,949 --> 00:08:08,860
With this bearish move, we drew a 50% retracement
zone, which also aligned with the VWAP

118
00:08:08,860 --> 00:08:13,470
As the price reached the confluence area,
we had a trendline breakout which offered

119
00:08:13,470 --> 00:08:17,570
additional confirmation that the bears are
in control of that area.

120
00:08:17,570 --> 00:08:22,240
Given the confluence of resistance levels
and VWAP, this trading signal was valid.

121
00:08:22,240 --> 00:08:26,889
More specifically, the entry timing offered
by the setup was appealing.

122
00:08:26,889 --> 00:08:32,860
The advantage here is that VWAP is more responsive
to price movements on significant volume versus

123
00:08:32,860 --> 00:08:34,730
those with less money behind them.

124
00:08:34,730 --> 00:08:40,970
As VWAP absorbs more price and volume data
over time, it becomes more resistant to random

125
00:08:40,970 --> 00:08:42,810
oscillations and sudden shifts

126
00:08:42,810 --> 00:08:54,850
Here are other examples of valid VWAP trades.

127
00:08:54,850 --> 00:09:08,500
One of the reasons I prefer trading with VWAP
is its ability to eliminate the noise that

128
00:09:08,500 --> 00:09:10,400
occurs throughout the trading session.

129
00:09:10,400 --> 00:09:15,710
Knowing the price at which a majority of the
volume has traded makes it easier to evaluate

130
00:09:15,710 --> 00:09:18,140
a good level to buy or sell.

131
00:09:18,140 --> 00:09:22,960
Also, remember that the best setups often
appear together or close to one another.

132
00:09:22,960 --> 00:09:28,400
By looking for a confluence of patterns, we
are able to identify the high quality setups.

133
00:09:28,400 --> 00:09:33,170
The point is that when you find clusters of
trading setups pointing in the same direction,

134
00:09:33,170 --> 00:09:34,730
you find quality.

135
00:09:34,730 --> 00:09:40,370
An additional tip is to focus trading this
setup on large-cap equities with sufficient

136
00:09:40,370 --> 00:09:46,540
average daily volume, typically familiar names
that move smoothly and follow VWAP levels.

137
00:09:46,540 --> 00:09:50,940
Also avoid pre and post market and the first
15 minutes after the open.

138
00:09:50,940 --> 00:09:57,560
VWAP tends to be jumpy and unreliable during
those periods while it establishes itself.

139
00:09:57,560 --> 00:10:02,260
Remember to apply money management rules when
trading based on the VWAP indicator, and it

140
00:10:02,260 --> 00:10:07,350
would hurt to look for additional confirmation
signals from candlestick patterns, chart patterns,

141
00:10:07,350 --> 00:10:10,090
or other price action signals.

142
